      "color": "6"
    },
    {
      "id": "harrison",
      "type": "file",
      "file": "99 - Reference/Release Authorities.md",
      "x": 900,
      "y": 150,
      "width": 300,
      "height": 250,
      "color": "6"
    },
    {
      "id": "tearline",
      "type": "file",
      "file": "03 - Sources/Source - DOW-UAP-D50 INDOPACOM Email April 2025.md",
      "x": 1300,
      "y": 150,
      "width": 300,
      "height": 250,
      "color": "5"
    },
    {
      "id": "asymmetry",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## Asymmetry\n\nA full MISREP can be 10 pages of structured operational data (D19 was 10 pages).\n\nThe ==tearline== that reaches public-facing release is often ==two sentences==:\n\n> 'US AIRCRAFT OBSERVED 1X POSS UAP FOR 12 SECONDS AT 2353Z, FLYING AT UNK ALTITUDE AND UNK SPEED, NO INTERFERENCE WAS NOTED.'\n\n(D50 INDOPACOM tearline, 10 Apr 2025)\n\nThis asymmetry between collected data and releasable data is the single most important constraint on public-facing UAP analysis.",
      "x": 1300,
      "y": 450,
      "width": 500,
      "height": 420,
      "color": "6"
    },
    {
      "id": "redactions",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## Redaction patterns\n\n==(b)(1) 1.4(a)== - operational national security; blacks out unit details, ATO numbers, callsigns, locations\n\n==(b)(3) 10 U.S.C. \u00a7130b== - personnel privacy for service members\n\n==(b)(6)== - personnel privacy more broadly\n\nResult: every released MISREP follows the same template, but most fields are blacked out. The surviving narrative is typically the GENTEXT/UAP and OBS LINE entries.",
      "x": 540,
      "y": 490,
      "width": 600,
      "height": 400,
      "color": "6"
    }
  ],
